50|$|With {{more than}} 85% of the Mexican land area defined as arid or {{semi-arid}} {{and a highly}} variable inter annual rainfall Mexico is also prone to <b>droughts,</b> especially <b>in</b> the northern areas.The most severe <b>droughts</b> <b>in</b> Mexico in recent decades coincide with the variations in Pacific sea-surface temperatures associated with El Niño. The economic and social and environmental impacts of <b>droughts</b> <b>in</b> Mexico are notable. In 1996, four years of below normal rainfall produced farms losses estimated at US$1 billion and interstate political between Sonora and Sinaloa.|$|R
